{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17519556","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17519556"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:12:54+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:12:54+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13040"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13040","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13040"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.16,0.05,0.59,0.08,0.12]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5477"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"39728"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5477","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5477"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13040"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"24197"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1074"},{"type":"tags","id":"2840"},{"type":"tags","id":"3077"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9286"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9643"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"39728","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/39728"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 70-year-old man presents to the neurology clinic with a three-year history of progressively worsening symptoms. He complains of stiffness, slowness of movement while performing daily chores, and a slight tremor in his right hand. His wife reports that he has difficulty with tasks that require fine motor skills, such as buttoning his shirt or writing. She also notices a decrease in his facial expressiveness and softer speech. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, the patient exhibits a resting tremor in his right hand, increased resistance to movement and periodic jerks are observed in intervals, instead of a smooth and swift movement and reduced arm swing while walking.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is a pathological characteristic feature of this disease?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Tau protiens","Oligoclonal bands","Lewy bodies","Basophilic inclusion bodies","Amyloid plaques"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe presentation of this patient is consistent with Parkinson\u0027s disease. It is a neurodegenerative disorder that mostly presents in later life with generalized slowing of movements (bradykinesia) and at least one other symptom of resting tremor or rigidity. The primary aetiology appears to be the accumulation of alpha-synuclein in various parts of the brain, primarily the substantia nigra, leading to degeneration and subsequent loss of dopamine in the basal ganglia that control muscle tone and movement. \u003Cstrong\u003ELewy bodies \u003C/strong\u003Eare abnormal protein aggregates primarily composed of alpha-synuclein. They are the pathological characteristic feature of Parkinson\u0027s disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe presence of\u003Cstrong\u003E Oligoclonal bands\u003C/strong\u003E implies an immunological response and they are not present in idiopathic Parkinsons Disease and are usually present in MS (95%). These bands are detected through electrophoresis of the CSF and are used as a diagnostic marker for MS.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBasophilic inclusion bodies \u003C/strong\u003Eare dense, basophilic-staining structures that can be observed within the cytoplasm of cells. They are often associated with certain viral infections, such as herpes simplex encephalitis. However, the symptoms, timeframe and clinical presentation in the case are not consistent with viral encephalitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETau proteins\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Eamyloid plaques\u003C/strong\u003E are characteristic features of Alzheimer\u0027s disease. Tau proteins become abnormally phosphorylated and form neurofibrillary tangles within nerve cells. These tangles contribute to the degeneration of brain cells and are characteristic features observed in the brains of individuals with Alzheimer\u0027s disease. Amyloid plaques are formed by the accumulation of beta-amyloid protein in the brain. These plaques are associated with neuroinflammation and the degeneration of brain cells.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Lewy body is the characteristic feature of Parkinson\u0027s disease."],"references":["Shahmoradian SH Lewis AJ Genoud C et al.\nLewy pathology in Parkinson\u0027s disease consists of crowded organelles and lipid membranes, Nat Neurosci. 2019; 22: 1099-1109.","Shrimanker I, Tadi P, S\u00e1nchez-Manso JC. Parkinsonism. [Updated 2022 Jun 7]"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"24197"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13040"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"24197","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/24197"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2023-10-06T02:41:48+10:30","updatedAt":"2023-10-06T02:41:48+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5477"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"39728"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links"